{"title_page": "John Stafford Smith", "text_new": "{{other people|John Smith}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name              = John Stafford Smith\n| image             = File:Stafford Smith.png\n| birth_date        = bapt. {{Birth date|1750|3|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place       = [[Gloucester]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|1836|9|21|1750|3|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[London]], UK\n| nationality       = British\n| occupation        = [[Composer]]\n| known_for         = Composed \"[[To Anacreon in Heaven|The Anacreontic Song]]\", later adopted as the tune of the [[national anthem]] of the United States\n}}\n\n'''John Stafford Smith''' (bapt. 30 March 1750{{spaced ndash}}21 September 1836) was a British [[composer]], church [[organist]], and early [[musicologist]]. He was one of the first serious collectors of manuscripts of works by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]].\n\nSmith is best known for writing the music for \"[[To Anacreon in Heaven|The Anacreontic Song]]\", which became the tune for the American patriotic song \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\" following the [[War of 1812]], and in 1931 was adopted as the [[national anthem]] of the United States.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSmith was baptised in [[Gloucester Cathedral]], England, on 30 March 1750, the son of Martin Smith, organist of Gloucester Cathedral from 1743 to 1782.  He attended the [[The King's School, Gloucester|Gloucester cathedral school]], where he became a boy-singer.  He furthered his career as a choir boy at the [[Chapel Royal]], London, and also studied under Dr. [[William Boyce (composer)|William Boyce]]. he was stupid and rude nobody liked him\n\n==Career==\nBy the 1770s he had gained a reputation as a composer and an organist.  He was elected as a member of the select [[Anacreontic Society]] which boasted amongst its membership [[Samuel Johnson]], [[James Boswell]] and Sir [[Joshua Reynolds]].\n\nIn the 1770s, Smith composed music for the society's constitutional song entitled \"[[To Anacreon in Heaven]]\" (The Anacreontic Song). The words were by [[Ralph Tomlinson]], the president of the society, and were inspired by the 6th-century BC Greek lyric poet, [[Anacreon]], who wrote odes on the pleasures of love and wine. The song became popular in Britain and also America following the establishment of several Anacreontic Societies there. Smith never married.\n\nSmith later became a Gentleman of the Chapel Royal in 1784, organist for the Chapel Royal in 1802 and [[Master of the Children]] in 1805. He also became [[Lay clerk|lay-vicar]] of [[Westminster Abbey]]. He was organist at the [[Three Choirs Festival]] held at Gloucester in 1790.\n\nSmith is considered to be the first Englishman to be a serious [[antiquarian]] and [[musicologist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-stafford-smith-mn0001694662 |title=John Stafford Smith |first=Chris |last=Morrison |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=25 July 2012 |quote=John Stafford Smith has been called 'virtually the first English musicologist.'\u2026 [He] remains a significant figure in American history as the composer of the tune that Francis Scott Key adapted into 'The Star-Spangled Banner', the national anthem of the United States.}}</ref> He began by publishing ''A Collection of English Song'' in 1779, which musicologist [[Nicholas Temperley]] called \"perhaps the first scholarly edition printed in England.\"<ref name=grove>[http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/subscriber/article/grove/music/26008 Nicholas Temperley, \"Smith, John Stafford,\" ''Oxford Music Online/Grove Music Online'', accessed 29 December 2015 (access by subscription).]</ref>  Smith's library included the ''Old Hall Manuscript'', [[Drexel 4175]], as well as a copy of ''Ulm Gesangbuch'' from 1538 that had belonged to [[Johann Sebastian Bach]].<ref name=grove/> He also collected works that dated back to the 12th century including some [[Gregorian chants]]. His publication ''Musica Antiqua'' (1812) included musical scores of works by [[Jacob Obrecht]], [[Adrian Willaert]], [[Jacob Clemens non Papa|Jacob Clemens]] and [[Crist\u00f3bal de Morales]] with historical notes on each piece. According to [[Vincent Duckles]], Smith's major contribution was \"to direct the attention of his readers to the importance of source studies.\"<ref name=grove/>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:JohnStaffordSmith01.jpg|thumb|right|John Stafford Smith's memorial in [[Gloucester Cathedral]]]]\nSmith died in 1836 at the age of eighty-six, his death allegedly caused by a grape-pip lodged in his windpipe. He is buried in [[Gloucester Cathedral]] and has a memorial plaque there, above which are displayed the [[Flag of the United States|US]] and [[Flag of the United Kingdom|UK's flags]].<ref>[https://www.mayflower400uk.org/news/2019/july/cathedral-to-ring-out-star-spangled-banner-in-honour-of-its-english-composer/ Mayflower 400]</ref><ref>[https://www.theamerican.co.uk/pr/ne-Star-Spangled-Banner-Gloucester ''The American'']</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n===National anthem of the United States===\nIn 1814, [[Francis Scott Key]] wrote the poem \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner|Defence of Fort M'Henry]]\" (later re-titled, \"The Star-Spangled Banner\") which was later set to the tune of \"Anacreon\", a piece composed by Smith. The US Congress officially designated this song as the US [[national anthem]] in 1931.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=John Stafford Smith: Composer of the Star Spangled Banner \n |url=http://www.visit-gloucestershire.co.uk/gloucester/smith.htm \n |publisher=Gloucestershire Portal \n |accessdate=25 July 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711181457/http://www.visit-gloucestershire.co.uk/gloucester/smith.htm \n |archivedate=11 July 2007 \n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.answers.com/topic/john-stafford-smith |title=AMG AllMusic Guide: Pop Artists: John Stafford Smith |last1=Johnson |first1=Keith |publisher=[[Answers.com|Answers]] |accessdate=25 July 2012}}\n* {{cite book |title=Historic Gloucester: An Illustrated Guide to the City & Its Buildings |last=Moss |first=Phillip |year=2005 |publisher=Nonsuch Publishing |location=Stroud, England |isbn=9781845880774 |oclc=318953639}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/manuscripts/search/results_n.cfm?NID=7345&RID=&Y1=&Y2= |title=Material relating to John Stafford Smith (search) |publisher=Special Collections Department, [[University of Glasgow]] |accessdate=25 July 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Smith,+John+Stafford | name=John Stafford Smith}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=John Stafford Smith |sopt=t}}\n* {{IMSLP|id=Smith, John Stafford|cname=John Stafford Smith}}\n* {{ChoralWiki}}\n* [http://dmr.bsu.edu/cdm/search/searchterm/Smith,%20John%20Stafford,%201750-1836/mode/exact Free John Stafford Smith sheet music] from the Ball State University Digital Media Repository\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Samuel Arnold (composer)|Samuel Arnold]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=First [[Organist]] of the [[Chapel Royal]]\n|years=1802\u20131836}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas Attwood (composer)|Thomas Attwood]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edmund Ayrton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Master of the Children]] of the [[Chapel Royal]]\n|years=1805\u20131817}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Hawes]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, John Stafford}}\n[[Category:1750 births]]\n[[Category:1836 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:18th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:18th-century English people]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English people]]\n[[Category:British classical composers]]\n[[Category:British male classical composers]]\n[[Category:British classical organists]]\n[[Category:Male organists]]\n[[Category:British musicologists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Gloucester Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Classical-period composers]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen of the Chapel Royal]]\n[[Category:Glee composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:National anthem writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Gloucester]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester]]\n[[Category:18th-century keyboardists]]\n[[Category:19th-century organists]]\n[[Category:British antiquarians]]\n[[Category:The Star-Spangled Banner]]\n[[Category:Masters of the Children of the Chapel Royal]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|John Smith}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name              = John Stafford Smith\n| image             = File:Stafford Smith.png\n| birth_date        = bapt. {{Birth date|1750|3|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place       = [[Gloucester]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|1836|9|21|1750|3|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[London]], UK\n| nationality       = British\n| occupation        = [[Composer]]\n| known_for         = Composed \"[[To Anacreon in Heaven|The Anacreontic Song]]\", later adopted as the tune of the [[national anthem]] of the United States\n}}\n\n'''John Stafford Smith''' (bapt. 30 March 1750{{spaced ndash}}21 September 1836) was a British [[composer]], church [[organist]], and early [[musicologist]]. He was one of the first serious collectors of manuscripts of works by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]].\n\nSmith is best known for writing the music for \"[[To Anacreon in Heaven|The Anacreontic Song]]\", which became the tune for the American patriotic song \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\" following the [[War of 1812]], and in 1931 was adopted as the [[national anthem]] of the United States.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSmith was baptised in